Fetching the HTML source code of a page that contains Shadow DOM web components can be a bit tricky, as the Shadow DOM encapsulates the DOM tree of the web component and makes it inaccessible to the outside world. However, there are a few approaches that you can try:

1. Use the browser's developer tools: Most modern web browsers (Chrome, Firefox, Safari, Edge) have developer tools that allow you to inspect the DOM tree of a page. In the Elements tab of the developer tools, you can select a web component that contains Shadow DOM and view its contents. You can then right-click on the selected element and choose "Copy -> Copy element" to copy the HTML source code of the web component.
2. Use a headless browser: A headless browser is a browser that can be used programmatically to navigate and interact with web pages. You can use a headless browser such as Puppeteer or Selenium to navigate to the web page and extract the HTML source code of the web component using JavaScript.

Here's an example using Puppeteer:
```javascript
const puppeteer = require('puppeteer');

(async () => {
  const browser = await puppeteer.launch();
  const page = await browser.newPage();
  await page.goto('https://example.com');
  const html = await page.evaluate(() => {
    const webComponent = document.querySelector('my-web-component');
    return webComponent.shadowRoot.innerHTML;
  });
  console.log(html);
  await browser.close();
})();
```
In this example, we're using Puppeteer to launch a headless browser, navigate to a web page, select a web component using its selector, and extract its Shadow DOM using the `shadowRoot` property.

1. Use a specialized tool: There are also specialized tools available, such as Web Scraper Chrome extension or web scraping libraries like BeautifulSoup or Scrapy, that can help you extract the HTML source code of a web page with Shadow DOM web components. These tools can work with the page as a whole and not just specific web components.

However, keep in mind that accessing Shadow DOM directly is not recommended, as it goes against the encapsulation principles and can break the intended behavior of the web component.

